## Codebase Patterns

- Sender-side commit creation lives in `src/create-commit.ts` (`createCommit`), which calls
  `applyProposals` (src/client-state.ts) to get an `ApplyProposalsResult` (`res`), then
  conditionally calls `createUpdatePath` (src/update-path.ts) when `res.needsUpdatePath` is true.
  Receiver-side commit processing is the mirror in `src/process-messages.ts` (`processCommit` ->
  `applyTreeUpdate` -> `updatePrivateKeyPath` -> `applyUpdatePathSecret`, the latter defined in
  create-commit.ts and shared by both join and commit-processing paths).
- When fixing a sender/receiver protocol asymmetry, always check both sides: the receiver in this
  codebase is frequently already more spec-correct than the sender (or vice versa), and the fix is
  to make the two sides compute the exact same thing, not just to "add a check." In this session's
  case, `process-messages.ts`/`create-commit.ts`'s `applyUpdatePathSecret` already excluded newly
  added leaves from a copath resolution via a `filterNewLeaves`/`excludeNodes` mechanism, but
  `update-path.ts`'s `createUpdatePath` (the encrypt side) did not call it — only the decrypt side
  filtered, so ciphertext array indices didn't line up once a resolution containing an excluded
  new leaf was involved.
- `ApplyProposalsResult.additionalResult` is a discriminated union (`kind: 'memberCommit' |
  'externalCommit' | 'reinit'`). For `'memberCommit'`, `addedLeafNodes:[LeafIndex, KeyPackage][]`
  gives you the leaves added by proposals in *this* commit — the canonical source for "which nodes
  are new" when a commit needs to treat added leaves specially (see US-002).
  `res.additionalResult.kind === 'memberCommit' ? res.additionalResult.addedLeafNodes.map((l) =>
  leafToNodeIndex(l[0])) : []` is the idiom used on both sender and receiver to build that list.
- `resolution(tree, nodeIndex)` (src/ratchet-tree.ts) walks a subtree: for a non-blank node it
  returns `[nodeIndex, ...unmergedLeaves]`; for a blank node it recurses into left/right children.
  The *order* of a resolution array is significant (it determines ciphertext index alignment
  between encryptor and decryptor), and is left-to-right / low-to-high leaf index by construction.
  To exercise a resolution ordering bug in a test, you need a blank parent node whose left child is
  the *new* leaf and whose right child is a *pre-existing* leaf — that puts the new (to-be-excluded)
  entry first, which is the ordering that actually shifts indices for anything filtered out earlier
  in the array. Getting a lower leaf index newly occupied while a higher leaf index stays occupied
  requires a prior Remove to free up a low slot before the Add executes in a later commit (adds
  always fill the *lowest* blank leaf index) — see test/scenario/add-with-path.ts for the recipe.
- Test scenarios live in `test/scenario/*.ts` and use `@substrate-system/tapzero`'s `test()`, one
  `test(...)` registered per ciphersuite via `for (const cs of Object.keys(ciphersuites))`, with a
  try/catch inside that skips `NotSupportedError`/`DependencyError` (unsupported ciphersuite in the
  current environment, e.g. X448/Ed448 in browsers) rather than failing the whole run. New files
  must be added to `test/index.ts` under `// Scenario tests` (plain side-effecting imports; nothing
  else wires them in) or they never run as part of `npm test`.
- To run a single new/edited scenario test file without paying for the full `npm test` bundle+run,
  bundle just that file's import with esbuild directly, e.g.:
  `printf "import '/abs/path/to/test/scenario/foo.js'\n" > /tmp/run.ts && npx esbuild /tmp/run.ts
  --bundle --platform=node --format=cjs --loader:.json=json --keep-names --outfile=/tmp/bundle.cjs
  && node /tmp/bundle.cjs`. Relative imports from the test file itself resolve fine; just the entry
  script needs an absolute path.
- `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` currently has one pre-existing, unrelated failure in
  `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` (an `Array.reduce` overload mismatch around `Promise<Epoch>`
  vs `Epoch`). This is not caused by story work in this project; don't try to fix it as a side
  effect of an unrelated story, and don't treat its presence as a sign your change broke
  typechecking — diff the tsc output before/after your change instead of just checking "any errors."
- Before starting any story, always run `git status`/`git diff` first. Across US-005, US-006,
  US-007, US-011, US-012, US-015, US-016, and US-017 the working tree already contained a
  fully-drafted (uncommitted) fix at session start every time -- apparently left over from an
  earlier session/pass that wrote the diff but stalled before verifying and committing it.
  `passes: false` in `specs/prd.json` does NOT mean no work exists yet. Review whatever is already
  in the working tree against the acceptance criteria (and still run the git-stash RED/GREEN
  verification on it, per TEST-FIRST) rather than assuming it's correct or reimplementing from
  scratch.
- When a story's drafted fix spans several `src/` files and a full `git stash` of all of them only
  produces a compile-time RED (missing export, etc.), that alone doesn't prove each individual file's
  change is behaviorally load-bearing. Stash-and-rerun one file at a time (keeping the others plus all
  test changes applied) to get a genuine runtime RED per file -- e.g. for US-017, stashing only
  `src/public-message.ts` (while `src/external-sender.ts`'s new vector codec stayed in place) produced
  a real runtime crash (`CodecError: Could not decode ExternalSender`) distinct from the whole-diff
  compile error, confirming that file's change was independently exercised by the tests, not just
  along for the ride.
- `git stash` does NOT touch untracked files by default (the new test file a drafted-but-uncommitted
  fix usually ships with is untracked). This is convenient, not a gap to work around: stashing just
  the modified `src/*.ts` files leaves the new test file in place and gives a genuine pre-fix RED run
  with zero extra bookkeeping (no `-u`, no manual copy-aside). Only reach for `git stash -u` if the
  drafted fix's test file itself was staged/tracked already.
- `src/treemath.ts`'s `root`/`parent`/`sibling`/`directPath`/`copath` only ever consume a numeric
  `leafWidth` through `root(leafWidth)` -> `nodeWidth(leafWidth)` -> `rootFromNodeWidth` ->
  `floor(log2(nodeWidth))`. For any real ratchet tree, `tree.length` is always odd
  (`2*leafCount - 1`), so a leaf-width computed as `tree.length / 2` (the classic "forgot to use
  `leafWidth()`" bug, e.g. old US-003/M1) is *always* exactly `leafCount - 0.5` — never more, never
  less. Because `floor(log2(2n))` and `floor(log2(2n+1))` are provably equal for every integer
  n >= 1 (the only way they'd differ is `2n+1` being an exact power of two, which is impossible for
  an odd number > 1), `root()` — and therefore every `directPath`/`copath` sequence derived from
  it — is mathematically identical whether you pass the correct integer leaf width or that
  buggy `x-0.5` value. Verified this empirically too (probe script iterating leaf counts 1..64,
  all leaf indices: zero divergence in root/directPath/copath output). Practical implication: a
  `-0.5`-style leafWidth bug in this codebase cannot be caught with a RED-before/GREEN-after
  integration test through `applyUpdatePath`/`filteredDirectPath` — the fix is still correct/required
  (wrong type, relies on a fragile coincidence, would break instantly if `directPath`/`copath` ever
  compared width directly instead of going through `root()`), but don't burn time hunting for an
  integration-level failing test for this exact bug shape. If a future story's acceptance criteria
  assumes a behavioral test must fail before such a fix, verify that assumption first (as done here)
  before trying to force one.
- When a story's acceptance criteria has been independently confirmed BLOCKED (criteria internally
  self-contradictory, e.g. mandates a change that breaks an already-passing spec-conformance test) by
  3+ sessions using different verification methods, a further session should not re-derive the same
  conclusion a fourth-plus time, and should also not unilaterally rescope `specs/prd.json`'s acceptance
  criteria to force a green result -- that is the same "reinterpret the requirement" anti-pattern rule 6
  forbids, just applied to the spec instead of the tests, and is especially wrong when the real choice
  is a product/security tradeoff (e.g. strict-interop-breaking vs. lenient-and-compatible) that
  reasonable engineers could land on differently, not a pure correctness question with one right answer.
  But *also* don't just append another near-identical "still blocked" pointer commit -- several of those
  in a row for the same story (see US-022) is itself a stall signal, not evidence of progress. Instead,
  escalate directly to the user in the session's chat response with a concrete, answerable question
  (the specific options, a recommendation, and what unblocks a future session), and consider suggesting
  the story be explicitly deprioritized in `specs/prd.json`'s ordering if no decision is forthcoming, so
  future sessions spend cycles on unblocked work instead of re-confirming the same wall.
- `ralph_claude.sh` (the loop runner) has a `manual:true` field convention on a `userStories[]` entry,
  fully wired into task selection: `current_task()` (`sort_by(.priority)` over
  `select(.passes == false and .manual != true)`) and `count_pending()` both skip any story with
  `manual: true`, and `pending_manual_list()`/the "only manual work left" exit path in the main loop
  report those stories separately with the instruction to run them via `./ralph_device.sh <id>` "in an
  attended session" (that script doesn't exist yet as of 2026-07-17 -- the reporting/gating logic is
  real and works today regardless, only the convenience wrapper is unwritten). This is the mechanism
  for exactly the situation the previous bullet describes: once a story is genuinely blocked on a
  human product/policy decision (not a technical gap further investigation could close), the
  responsible move for the session that confirms "no decision is forthcoming" is to set `manual: true`
  on that story (leave `passes: false`, leave acceptance criteria untouched -- this is not "forcing
  green," it's the opposite: an honest admission autonomous work cannot resolve this one) rather than
  writing an eighth near-identical "still blocked" pointer commit. This actually changes loop behavior
  (verified by simulating `current_task()`'s jq query against the edited file before committing --
  it now resolves to the next-priority non-manual story), unlike a pointer commit which does not.
  Unset `manual` once a human has made the call, whether that's implementing the deferred fix or
  simply recording a decision in the story's `notes`.
- When a story adds a new *strict* validation check gated on a threaded `sentByClient`/similar flag,
  and that check runs against a widely-imported default/fixture constant (e.g. US-026's
  `defaultLifetime`, imported by ~40 files across `test/scenario/` and `test/validation/`), grep
  every usage of that constant before trusting a drafted fix. The constant itself may need
  adjusting to satisfy the new check, and that adjustment is in-scope -- required by the "Tests
  pass" acceptance criterion -- even though the acceptance criteria only name the validation
  function, not the fixture. Verify (a) no test asserts the fixture's specific old literal values
  before changing them, and (b) the new value has comfortable margin under the new limit (not
  barely passing) so the change isn't flaky. Verify each file's change is independently load-bearing
  via the existing "stash one file at a time" technique: stashing just the validation-logic file
  should RED the new test; stashing just the fixture file (with the validation fix in place) should
  RED an unrelated *pre-existing* test that exercises the fixture through the newly-strict path.
- When a drafted-but-uncommitted fix adds `.fill(0)` zeroization of a secret buffer that is a
  `const`-bound reference shared across multiple later statements in the same function (not a
  private local consumed once), trace EVERY later read of that same variable/array before trusting
  the zero call's placement, not just the read(s) immediately before it. US-028's drafted
  `createCommit` fix computed `commitSecret` from `pathSecrets` then called `zeroPathSecretsArray
  (pathSecrets)` immediately after -- correct with respect to `commitSecret`, but `pathSecrets` was
  *also* passed by reference into `createWelcome` (called ~50 lines later) which reads
  `pathSecret.secret` per new member to build their `EncryptedGroupSecrets`; the zero call ran
  before that second, non-adjacent read, so every new member added by a commit that also required an
  UpdatePath silently received an all-zero path secret in their Welcome. `.fill(0)` mutates the
  underlying buffer for every reference to it, so the bug doesn't show up as a type error or an
  obviously-wrong local value -- it only manifests three function calls away, as the *new joiner*
  deriving a private key that doesn't match what the committer's tree actually contains. Confirmed
  via a direct probe (compare the committer's and new joiner's exported private key bytes for their
  shared ancestor node -- they must be byte-identical) rather than trusting an HPKE-roundtrip-style
  test assertion, since that kind of assertion is easy to accidentally make non-load-bearing (see
  next bullet). Fix: move the zero call to after the last real consumer (`createWelcome`), not
  right after the first.
- This project's established `skippable(error)` convention, used identically across every
  `test/scenario/*.ts` file, checks ONLY `error?.name === 'NotSupportedError' || error?.name ===
  'DependencyError'` (environment/ciphersuite-support gaps, e.g. X448/Ed448 in browsers -- see the
  existing Codebase Patterns bullet on this). A drafted test file that broadens this (e.g. also
  catching `CryptoError`/`DeriveKeyPairError`/message-substring checks) will silently swallow a real
  regression if that regression happens to manifest as one of the extra caught types -- which is
  exactly what happened in US-028: the drafted `key-material-retention.ts` test's widened
  `skippable()` caught the `CryptoError` (`OpenError: invalid tag`/`OpenError: operation failed`)
  that the premature-zeroing bug above produces on its HPKE round-trip probe, logging it as a
  per-ciphersuite skip (`t.comment(...)`) instead of failing the test -- so the one assertion that
  would have caught the bug never ran, across all 19 ciphersuites, and the draft's own regression
  test appeared to pass 100% both with and without the bug present. When reviewing (or writing) a
  scenario/validation test's `skippable`-style catch-all, diff its error-name set against the
  established `NotSupportedError`/`DependencyError`-only convention before trusting a "0 failures"
  result from it -- a broadened catch is a red flag, not a robustness improvement.
- This repo has no `package-lock.json` tracked in git or present in the working directory
  (`git ls-files | grep -i lock` is empty). `npm audit`/`npm install` operate directly against
  whatever is locally resolved in `node_modules` -- there is no lockfile to diff or commit for a
  dependency-bump/removal story here.
- `SECURITY-AUDIT.md`'s `- [ ]` checkboxes are never flipped to `[x]` when a finding is fixed --
  confirmed unchecked across the entire file even for findings fixed and committed many stories ago
  (US-001 through US-029). It is a frozen point-in-time audit snapshot, not a live tracker;
  `progress.log`/`specs/prd.json` are the actual source of truth for fix status. Don't edit
  SECURITY-AUDIT.md's checkboxes when closing out a story.

## 2026-07-17 - US-002

- Implemented: excluded leaves added by the current commit from each copath resolution on the
  sender side, so `createCommit`'s (and `joinGroupExternal`'s) `createUpdatePath` call now produces
  an `encrypted_path_secret` vector whose length/order matches what the receiver already expects.
- Files changed:
  - `src/update-path.ts`: `createUpdatePath` gains an `excludeNodes:NodeIndex[] = []` parameter;
    its `filteredDirectPathAndCopathResolution` result is mapped through a new exported
    `filterNewLeaves(resolution, excludeNodes)` helper before being folded into `PathSecret.sendTo`
    (which `encryptSecretsForPath` later encrypts to verbatim, so no changes were needed there).
  - `src/create-commit.ts`: removed its private duplicate `filterNewLeaves` (now imported from
    `update-path.js`); `createCommit` computes `addedLeafNodeIndices` from
    `res.additionalResult.addedLeafNodes` (memberCommit case only; `[]` otherwise) and passes it as
    `excludeNodes` to `createUpdatePath`. The `joinGroupExternal` call site passes no excludeNodes
    (defaults to `[]`) since an external commit's own new leaf is never in its own copath.
  - `test/scenario/add-with-path.ts` (new): builds `[alice, bob, eve, charlie]`, removes eve and
    adds dave in the same commit (forces both an UpdatePath and puts dave, the new leaf, ahead of
    charlie, a pre-existing member, in a shared blank parent's copath resolution), then asserts
    charlie can `processPublicMessage` the commit and reach the same `epochAuthenticator` as alice.
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new scenario test.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-002 `passes: true` with implementation notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - Verified TDD properly: ran the new test against the pre-fix code (via `git stash`) and
    confirmed it fails with `CryptoError: OpenError: The operation failed for an operation-specific
    reason` thrown from `applyUpdatePathSecret`'s HPKE `open` call — i.e. the receiver decrypts the
    wrong ciphertext slot because of the index misalignment. After `git stash pop` (restoring the
    fix) the same test passes across all ciphersuites.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 44756 assertions) and `npm run lint` both pass after the change.
  - See the new "Sender-side commit creation..." and "resolution(tree, ...) order matters..." bullets
    added to `## Codebase Patterns` above for reusable detail on this exclusion mechanism and how to
    reproduce ordering-sensitive resolution bugs in a test.
---

## 2026-07-17 - US-003
- Implemented: verified the leaf-width fix required by the acceptance criteria
  (`src/ratchet-tree.ts:248`, `filteredDirectPath`, use `leafWidth(tree.length)` instead of
  `nodeToLeafIndex(toNodeIndex(tree.length))`) was already present in the working tree from a prior
  uncommitted "wip" pass (committed at `14e7050`), along with its sibling function
  `filteredDirectPathAndCopathResolution`. Confirmed via `grep` that no remaining
  `nodeToLeafIndex(toNodeIndex(tree.length))` leaf-width pattern exists anywhere in `src/`. The
  only uncommitted work needed was the regression test, which had also been drafted (but not
  committed) in a prior session.
- Files changed:
  - `test/scenario/leaf-width-update-path.ts` (was already present, untracked -- kept as-is, no
    edits needed): builds a 4-leaf tree (`tree.length === 7`), asserts `leafWidth(7) === 4` diverges
    numerically from the buggy `nodeToLeafIndex(toNodeIndex(7)) === 3.5`, then runs a full
    UpdatePath commit (`createCommit` with no extra proposals -- an empty-proposal commit still
    requires a path per US-001's `needsUpdatePath`) and has three receivers (`processPrivateMessage`)
    apply it, asserting `epochAuthenticator` convergence and HPKE key matching across all of them,
    plus `testEveryoneCanMessageEveryone`.
  - `test/index.ts` (was already modified, uncommitted): registers the new scenario import.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-003 `passes: true` with notes explaining the mathematical-inertness
    finding below.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - TDD verification for this story could NOT follow the standard RED-before/GREEN-after shape:
    temporarily reverted just the `filteredDirectPath` line back to the buggy expression and reran
    the new test -- it still passed (532/532), exactly as predicted by the treemath analysis added
    to `## Codebase Patterns` above. Wrote a standalone probe script iterating leaf counts 1..64 and
    all leaf indices comparing `directPath`/`copath`/`root` output between the buggy and correct
    leaf-width values directly via `src/treemath.ts` -- zero divergence found, confirming the bug is
    mathematically inert for the current implementation (see the new Codebase Patterns bullet for
    the full proof sketch). Restored the fix before proceeding.
  - Given the above, the added test provides honest value in two ways instead of a RED/GREEN
    demonstration: (1) a direct, currently-true numeric assertion that the buggy and correct
    leaf-width expressions diverge at this tree size (documents *why* the fix in the diff is
    correct even though it's not observably load-bearing today), and (2) real integration coverage
    of `applyUpdatePath`/`filteredDirectPath` at a tree size (4 leaves, `tree.length` odd and not a
    power-of-two-minus-one boundary) that wasn't previously exercised by the test suite, guarding
    against a *future* regression that breaks the coincidence (e.g. if `directPath`/`copath` were
    ever changed to compare width directly against a node index instead of only through `root()`).
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45288 assertions) and `npm run lint` both pass.
