## 2026-07-17 - US-004
- Implemented: the RFC 9420 SS7.9.2 "resolution / unmerged-leaves" criterion for
  parent-hash verification, which was previously entirely missing -- only the hash-chain
  equality and single-coverage checks existed.
- Files changed:
  - `src/treemath.ts`: added `leafRange(nodeIndex): [LeafIndex, LeafIndex]`, a structural
    helper (descends via `left`/`right` down to leaves) that returns the inclusive leaf-index
    range spanned by a node's subtree, independent of which nodes in that subtree are blank.
  - `src/parent-hash.ts`: added `satisfiesResolutionCriterion(tree, d, p, c)` implementing the
    spec text verbatim -- "D is in the resolution of C, and the intersection of P's
    unmerged_leaves with the subtree under C is equal to the resolution of C with D removed"
    (`sameNodeIndexSet` does the set-equality comparison, order-independent). Wired into
    `parentHashCoverage`'s per-leaf bottom-up walk: `c` (P's child on D's side) is computed the
    same way `calculateParentHash` already computes `siblingIndex` (S), just for the opposite
    branch (`currentIndex < parentHashNodeIndex ? left(...) : right(...)`), then the new check
    is ANDed into the existing hash-equality condition gating whether a link counts as valid
    coverage.
  - `test/validation/parent-hash-resolution.ts` (new): builds a real 4-leaf group (alice, bob,
    charlie, dave) with an UpdatePath commit so alice's leaf has a genuine `leaf_node_source:
    'commit'` parent-hash chain to the root, sanity-checks the honest tree validates and bob
    converges, then tampers with the ROOT parent node's `unmergedLeaves` to add bob's leaf index
    (1) -- which is on the *other* side of root's own children (node 1, alice+bob) from the
    sibling side the existing hash-chain check actually recomputes a tree hash over (node 5,
    charlie+dave), so the tamper is invisible to the pre-existing hash-chain check but violates
    the new resolution/unmerged-leaves intersection criterion. Recomputes `treeHashRoot` from the
    tampered tree so the tree-hash check also stays self-consistent (mirrors a real malicious
    inviter crafting both the tree and its GroupInfo `tree_hash` together). Registered in
    `test/index.ts` under "Validation tests".
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - Verified TDD properly: `git stash`-ed `src/parent-hash.ts` and `src/treemath.ts` only (kept
    the new/edited test files), rebuilt with the single-file esbuild-bundle recipe from
    "Codebase Patterns", and got 19 failing assertions (one per ciphersuite) with the exact
    fix reverted; `git stash pop` restored the fix and all 57 assertions in the new file passed.
  - Constructing a *minimal* attack tree for this criterion is fiddly: `getParentHash()` returns
    `undefined` (and the per-leaf walk in `parentHashCoverage` immediately `break`s) for any leaf
    whose `leafNodeSource !== 'commit'` -- i.e. plain `key_package`-sourced leaves (bob, charlie,
    dave in a fresh join) never contribute *any* coverage on their own walk. In a small group only
    the committer's own leaf (freshly re-keyed to `'commit'` source by its own UpdatePath) walks
    all the way to the root, so that is the only leaf whose walk needs to be reasoned about when
    picking which node/link to tamper with for a targeted test.
  - When picking which `unmerged_leaves` entry to forge for an attack test, the entry must land
    under the child (`C`) on the *checked node's own side* of the parent, not the sibling (`S`)
    side -- forging an entry under the `S` side changes `originalSiblingTreeHash` and trips the
    *existing* hash-chain check instead (a different, already-covered failure mode), which is not
    what "passes the hash chain but violates the new criterion" requires.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45345 assertions), `npm run lint`, and `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only
    the pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` error, unchanged) all pass.
