## 2026-07-17 - US-005
- Implemented: range-validation for every decoded `unmergedLeaves` entry in a `RatchetTree`
  (rejecting the whole tree at decode time if any entry is out of range), plus defensive bounds
  guards in `treemath`'s `level`/`parent`/`directPath` so an out-of-range node index throws a
  `ValidationError` instead of the 32-bit-bitwise-wraparound infinite loop described in
  SECURITY-AUDIT.md H3.
- Found this story's implementation already done, uncommitted, in the working tree at session
  start (`src/ratchet-tree.ts`, `src/treemath.ts`, `test/codec/ratchet-tree.ts` all showed as
  modified-but-uncommitted in `git status`). Reviewed it in full against the acceptance criteria
  and SECURITY-AUDIT.md's H3 section rather than assuming it was correct, then verified it properly
  (see below) before committing.
- Files changed:
  - `src/ratchet-tree.ts`: `decodeRatchetTree` now goes through the new `mapDecoderOption` (added
    to `src/codec/tls-decoder.ts` in a prior, already-committed change -- confirmed present) instead
    of `mapDecoder`, so `extendRatchetTree`'s output can be rejected wholesale. New
    `unmergedLeavesInRange(tree)` helper walks every parent node and checks each
    `unmergedLeaves` entry is `Number.isInteger`, `>= 0`, and `< leafWidth(tree.length)`; decode
    returns `undefined` (i.e. the whole tree is rejected) if any entry fails. This is the single
    choke point all `RatchetTree`-embedded indices flow through on the wire, so gating here means
    `resolution()`/`encryptSecretsForPath`/etc. downstream never see an out-of-range index from an
    untrusted tree.
  - `src/treemath.ts`: new `assertValidNodeIndex` (private) rejects non-integer, negative, or
    `>= 0x80000000` node indices before `level()`'s bit-shift loop runs -- JS's bitwise operators
    coerce to signed 32-bit ints, so `0xFFFFFFFF` (or anything `>= 2^31`) silently becomes negative
    and `level()`'s `while (((nodeIndex >> k) & 0x01) === 1)` loop condition is then permanently
    true (unbounded hang). `parent()` and `directPath()` additionally reject any `nodeIndex` outside
    `[0, nodeWidth(leafWidth))` up front (a value could be a small *positive* int32 and still be
    nonsensical for the tree's actual width, which `assertValidNodeIndex` alone wouldn't catch).
  - `test/codec/ratchet-tree.ts`: added a decode-rejection test (1-leaf tree, parent node's
    `unmergedLeaves: [0xFFFFFFFF]`) asserting `decodeRatchetTree` returns `undefined`, and a
    treemath test asserting `directPath(toNodeIndex(0xFFFFFFFF), 4)` throws a `ValidationError`
    (not a hang). Already registered in `test/index.ts` (existing file, not new).
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-005 `passes: true` with notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - Verified TDD properly despite the code already being present: `git stash push -- src/ratchet-tree.ts src/treemath.ts`
    (kept the test file), reran via the single-file esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns.
    Pre-fix, the malicious tree *decodes successfully* (the bug), so `t.equal(decoded, undefined)`
    fails -- the test runner then crashes trying to `JSON.stringify` the failing assertion's diff
    output because the decoded `LeafNode`'s `lifetime` fields are `BigInt`s (unrelated pre-existing
    tapzero/BigInt limitation, not a bug in this change), but the `not ok` line is emitted before
    that crash, confirming the test genuinely fails pre-fix rather than silently passing. `git stash
    pop` restored the fix; all assertions pass post-fix.
  - Per SECURITY-AUDIT.md H3, `unmergedLeaves` is decoded via `decodeUint32` in
    `src/parent-node.ts` (full unsigned 32-bit value, no int32 wraparound at the decode step itself
    -- the wraparound only happens later, inside treemath's bitwise ops). Confirmed `0xFFFFFFFF`
    round-trips through `encodeUint32`/`decodeUint32` as the full unsigned value `4294967295`, so the
    range check in `unmergedLeavesInRange` (`leafIndex < width`, plain numeric comparison) catches it
    correctly without needing to account for int32 truncation itself.
  - The acceptance criteria's "every decoded node/leaf index" is scoped by SECURITY-AUDIT.md H3 to
    `unmergedLeaves` specifically (the only attacker-controlled index embedded *inside* a decoded
    `RatchetTree`); other decoded leaf indices in the codebase (e.g. `SenderData.leafIndex` in
    `message-protection.ts`) are a different, already-tracked concern (see US-009's
    `validateSenderData` enforcement) and out of scope here.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45348 assertions), `npm run lint`, and `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only the
    pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` error, unchanged) all pass.
