## 2026-07-17 - US-009

- Implemented: `unprotectPrivateMessage` (src/message-protection.ts) previously called
  `validateSenderData(senderData, ratchetTree)` at line 236 and discarded its return value, so a
  `PrivateMessage` whose decrypted `SenderData.leafIndex` pointed at a blank (or out-of-range) leaf
  was silently accepted. Wrapped the call in the existing `throwIfDefined` helper (imported from
  `src/client-state.ts`, the same helper `create-commit.ts`/`process-messages.ts` already use for
  this `MlsError | undefined` "validate-then-throw" idiom) so the `ValidationError` is now actually
  raised.
- Files changed: `src/message-protection.ts` (enforce the check), `test/test-vectors/message-protection.ts`
  (new `applicationWithBlankLeafSenderRejected` test + `ValidationError` import).
- Test-first: added `applicationWithBlankLeafSenderRejected`, which calls `protectApplicationData`
  for leaf index 1 (producing a validly-encrypted `PrivateMessage`), then calls
  `unprotectPrivateMessage` with a ratchet tree that has a blank node at that leaf's node index and
  asserts a `ValidationError` is thrown. Confirmed RED (test failed, `t.fail` hit) against the
  pre-existing code before the one-line fix, then GREEN after.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - `throwIfDefined` (the `(err:MlsError | undefined) => void` helper used throughout the codebase
    for "validate function returns `MlsError | undefined`; caller must throw it") lives in
    `src/client-state.ts`, not `src/mls-error.ts` where the error classes themselves live. Lower-level
    modules like `message-protection.ts` importing it from `client-state.ts` is an already-established
    pattern (`create-commit.ts` and `process-messages.ts` do the same) and does not create a circular
    import, since `client-state.ts` does not import `message-protection.ts` (or anything that does)
    at module scope.
  - `test/test-vectors/message-protection.ts` already had a `// need to provide a ratchet tree with
    non blank leaf node so senderData validation doesn't fail` comment on its shared
    `treeForLeafIndex1` fixture -- a sign this exact gap (the unenforced `validateSenderData` result)
    was anticipated by whoever wrote the original fixture, even though nothing exercised the negative
    case (blank leaf -> rejection) before this session.
  - To construct a `PrivateMessage` whose sender points at a blank leaf without needing a full
    multi-party group/commit flow, call `protectApplicationData` directly with a `leafIndex` that
    simply isn't backed by a leaf node in the `RatchetTree` you later pass to `unprotectPrivateMessage`
    -- `protectApplicationData`/`protect` only need a `SecretTree` node at that index (independent of
    the `RatchetTree`), so you can encrypt "as" a leaf index that's blank in the tree used for
    decryption. This is the cheapest way to unit-test sender-validation failures in
    `message-protection.ts` without spinning up `createGroup`/`joinGroup`/`createCommit`.
