## 2026-07-17 - US-010
- Enforced canonical (minimal) QUIC-varint length encoding on decode per RFC 9420 section
  2.1.2. `determineLength` in `src/codec/variable-length.ts` now checks the decoded length
  against the minimum value representable by the field size it was read from: a 2-byte length
  prefix must encode a value >= 64 (otherwise the 1-byte form was minimal), and a 4-byte length
  prefix must encode a value >= 16384 (otherwise the 2-byte form was minimal). Non-minimal
  encodings now throw `CodecError`. `decodeVarLenData` (and everything built on it, including
  `decodeVarLenType`) inherits this check for free since it calls `determineLength` internally.
- Files changed: `src/codec/variable-length.ts`, `test/codec/var-length-encoding.ts`.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - The length-prefix format here is TLS/QUIC-varint-style: prefix bits `00`/`01`/`10` select a
    1/2/4-byte length field with 6/14/30 usable value bits (an 8-byte `11` form exists in the
    format but is explicitly unsupported/rejected by this codebase, not part of this story).
    Minimality means: a value only ever uses the *smallest* field size that can represent it, so
    the valid ranges per field size are non-overlapping (`[0,63]`, `[64,16383]`,
    `[16384,0x3FFFFFFF]`); decode-side minimality enforcement is just checking the decoded value
    against the lower bound of its field size's range.
  - `test/codec/var-length-encoding.ts` already has an `arrayRoundtrip`/`varLenRoundtrip` harness
    built on `createRoundtripTest` (test/codec/roundtrip.ts) plus a handful of `t.throws(...)`
    negative tests directly against `determineLength`/`decodeVarLenData` -- new codec edge-case
    tests fit naturally alongside the existing `t.throws` block rather than needing a new file.
  - Running the full `npm test` (esbuild bundle of `test/index.ts` + node run of the ~45k
    assertion suite) took roughly 3 minutes of wall-clock/CPU time in this session -- slower than
    prior sessions' logged baselines suggested at a glance. Don't assume something is hung if
    `ps` shows the `node .test-bundle.cjs` process alive and its CPU time is still climbing;
    just keep waiting rather than killing it.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45572 assertions) and `npm run lint` both pass after the change.
    `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` shows only the pre-existing unrelated
    `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` error.
