## 2026-07-17 - US-011
- Implemented: hardened `decodeOptional`/`encodeOptional` (src/codec/optional.ts) per M4/M5.
  `decodeOptional` now bounds-checks before reading the presence octet (fails cleanly on a
  truncated buffer instead of optional-chaining past a missing byte) and rejects any presence
  octet other than 0 or 1 (previously any non-1 value was silently treated as "absent" via a
  bare `else`). `encodeOptional` now checks `t !== undefined` instead of a JS truthiness check
  (previously a legitimately-present-but-falsy value, e.g. `0`, was wrongly encoded as absent).
- Found this story's fix already drafted, uncommitted, in the working tree at session start
  (`src/codec/optional.ts`, `test/codec/optional.ts` both modified) -- the same recurring
  "stalled prior session" pattern documented across US-005 through US-008 in Codebase Patterns.
  This session's REASONING note said the task had "stalled repeatedly," yet no dated progress.log
  entry existed yet for US-011 -- consistent with a prior pass being interrupted before ever
  writing to progress.log or committing. Reviewed the draft in full against all four acceptance
  criteria and traced every call site before trusting it, rather than assuming correctness or
  redoing the work from scratch (per the systematic-debugging skill's Phase 1/2: understand what's
  there and why it might have stalled, before touching anything).
- Files changed:
  - `src/codec/optional.ts`: `decodeOptional` first calls `decodeUint8(b, offset)` and returns
    `undefined` immediately if that itself returns `undefined` (out-of-range read), rather than
    optional-chaining straight to `?.[0]` and silently falling through to the "absent" branch. The
    presence-octet check changed from an implicit "anything other than 1 means absent" (bare
    `else`) to an explicit three-way branch: `1` -> decode the value, `0` -> absent, anything else
    -> `undefined` (reject the whole decode). `encodeOptional`'s ternary condition changed from
    `(t ? ... : ...)` to `(t !== undefined ? ... : ...)`.
  - `test/codec/optional.ts`: added three new tests -- (1) `optional codec roundtrip falsy present
    value: 0` exercises the `encodeOptional` truthiness bug directly (value `0` through
    encodeUint8/decodeUint8), (2) `decodeOptional rejects presence octets other than 0 or 1`
    (presence octets 2 and 255 against decodeUint8), (3) `decodeOptional bounds-checks before
    reading the presence octet` (empty buffer, and reading at an offset one past the end of a
    1-byte buffer).
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-011 `passes: true` with notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - Verified TDD properly despite the code being pre-drafted: `git stash push -- src/codec/optional.ts`
    (kept the test file), rebuilt via the single-file esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns
    against `test/codec/optional.ts` directly -- a plain codec test file, not a scenario/validation
    test, but the same recipe applies unchanged since it's just an ordinary side-effecting tapzero
    import (`printf "import '/abs/path/to/test/codec/optional.js'\n" > /tmp/run.ts && npx esbuild
    /tmp/run.ts --bundle --platform=node --format=cjs --loader:.json=json --keep-names --outfile=/tmp/bundle.cjs
    && node /tmp/bundle.cjs`). Got 6 failing assertions pre-fix (byte-length + roundtrip-value for
    the falsy-0 case, both presence-octet-rejection assertions, both bounds-check assertions) --
    confirming the draft's tests are a real RED, not a tautology. `git stash pop` restored the fix;
    all 35 assertions in the file passed post-fix.
  - `decodeUint8` (src/codec/number.ts) already returns `undefined` on an out-of-range offset via
    `b.at(offset)` (which itself returns `undefined` past the end of the array), so decodeOptional's
    new bounds-check is just "propagate the existing `undefined` instead of optional-chaining past
    it" -- no change was needed in `number.ts` itself.
  - Checked every other call site of `encodeOptional`/`decodeOptional` in `src/` (group-secrets.ts,
    commit.ts, ratchet-tree.ts, tree-hash.ts) before trusting that the truthiness -> `!== undefined`
    change wouldn't alter existing runtime behavior: all of them wrap object-typed encoders
    (VarLenData/Uint8Array, UpdatePath, Node, LeafNode, ParentNode), and a JS object/typed-array is
    always truthy regardless of contents/length, so none of the existing callers were ever affected
    by the truthiness bug in practice -- only a caller passing a primitive falsy value (like the new
    test's literal `0` via encodeUint8) could trigger it. This is a pure hardening fix with no
    observable behavior change for existing callers, consistent with the story's "harden" framing.
  - This is now (at least) the fifth story in this project (after US-005 through US-008) where a
    security-audit fix was found already fully drafted, uncommitted, in the working tree at session
    start -- reconfirms the existing Codebase Patterns bullet on this; nothing new to add there.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45580 assertions -- exactly the US-010 baseline of 45572 plus the 8 new
    assertions), `npm run lint`, and `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only the pre-existing, documented
    `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` error, unchanged) all pass. Full suite took ~2m56s
    wall-clock this run -- consistent with the "don't assume hung" note logged under US-010.
