## 2026-07-17 - US-017
- Implemented: RFC 9420 SS12.1.8.2 says the `external_senders` GroupContext extension is a single
  extension whose payload is a variable-length vector of `ExternalSender` entries, and `SenderIndex`
  (on an `external`-sender `FramedContent`) indexes into that vector. The pre-fix code instead treated
  each `ExternalSender` as living in its *own* separate `external_senders`-typed extension, and indexed
  `SenderIndex` into the filtered *list of extensions* -- wrong per spec, and unable to represent more
  than one external sender without emitting duplicate-typed extensions (which nothing else in the
  codebase does).
- Found this story's fix already fully drafted, uncommitted, in the working tree at session start
  (`src/client-state.ts`, `src/external-proposal.ts`, `src/external-sender.ts`, `src/index.ts`,
  `src/public-message.ts`, and six test files all modified) -- the same recurring pattern documented
  in Codebase Patterns (now an eighth occurrence, after US-005 through US-008, US-011, US-012, US-015,
  US-016). This session's REASONING note said the task had "stalled once already." Reviewed the full
  diff against all acceptance criteria and grepped for every remaining `encodeExternalSender`/
  `decodeExternalSender`/`external_senders`/`senderFromExtension` call site in `src/` and `test/`
  before trusting it, rather than assuming correctness or redoing the work (systematic-debugging
  Phase 1/2).
- Files changed (all pre-drafted, verified then committed as-is):
  - `src/external-sender.ts`: added `encodeExternalSenders`/`decodeExternalSenders`, built from the
    existing `encodeVarLenType`/`decodeVarLenType` combinators (the same vector-of-items pattern used
    elsewhere in the codec layer) wrapping the pre-existing per-entry `encodeExternalSender`/
    `decodeExternalSender`.
  - `src/public-message.ts`: `senderFromExtension` now finds the single `external_senders` extension
    (`.find`, not `.filter`), decodes its data as a vector, and returns `decoded[0][senderIndex]` --
    indexing into the vector, not into a list of extensions. Out-of-range `senderIndex` now falls out
    naturally as `undefined` (JS array out-of-bounds access), already handled by the existing caller in
    `findSignaturePublicKey` (`if (sender === undefined) throw new ValidationError(...)`).
  - `src/client-state.ts`: `validateExternalSenders` updated to decode the one extension as a vector
    and loop over every entry in `decoded[0]`, instead of looping over multiple *extensions* each
    decoded as a single `ExternalSender`.
  - `src/external-proposal.ts`: `proposeExternal` updated to find the one extension, decode it as a
    vector (wrapped in try/catch so a throw during decode becomes the same `ValidationError` a
    graceful `undefined` decode would have produced), then `findIndex` the matching sender's
    `signaturePublicKey` *within* the vector, instead of `findIndex`-ing across extensions each
    decoded individually.
  - `src/index.ts`: exports the new `encodeExternalSenders`/`decodeExternalSenders` alongside the
    existing singular versions (the singular per-entry codec is still used directly by the vector
    combinator and by `test/codec/external-sender.ts`'s existing single-entry roundtrip tests, so it
    was kept, not removed).
  - `test/codec/external-sender.ts`: two new tests satisfy the "confirm the encoder matches the
    decoder (round-trip test with two external senders)" acceptance criterion directly -- a
    `createRoundtripTest(encodeExternalSenders, decodeExternalSenders)` roundtrip over `[basic, x509]`,
    and a second test asserting `senderIndex` 0/1 resolve to the correct entry after an
    encode-then-decode cycle.
  - Six test files (`test/scenario/cross-group-replay.ts`, `external-add-proposal.ts`,
    `external-proposal.ts`, `external-sender-policy.ts`, `reject-incoming-message.ts`, and
    `test/validation/proposal-validation.ts`): every fixture that builds an `external_senders`
    extension now calls `encodeExternalSenders([singleSender])` instead of
    `encodeExternalSender(singleSender)`, since a lone `ExternalSender` encoding is no longer a valid
    `external_senders` extension payload under the new (correct) format.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-017 `passes: true` with notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - Verified TDD properly: bundled the seven affected test files (`test/codec/external-sender.ts`,
    `test/validation/proposal-validation.ts`, and five `test/scenario/*.ts` files) via the single-file
    esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns and confirmed 862/862 assertions pass with the fix
    applied. Then `git stash push -- ` all five changed `src/` files (keeping every test change) and
    reran the same bundle: the build itself failed to compile (`No matching export in
    "src/external-sender.ts" for import "encodeExternalSenders"`) -- a legitimate RED, same shape as
    US-006's finding. Additionally stashed *only* `src/public-message.ts` (keeping the other four
    `src/` fixes and all test changes applied) and reran: this time the build succeeded but the run
    crashed with `CodecError: Could not decode ExternalSender` thrown from the old (reverted)
    `senderFromExtension` when fed the new vector-wrapped extension payload -- a genuine *runtime* RED
    specific to that one file's change, distinct from the whole-diff compile error. Restored both
    stashes (`git stash pop` each time) and reconfirmed 862/862 GREEN before proceeding. See the new
    Codebase Patterns bullet on per-file stash isolation added above.
  - Confirmed by hand-tracing the codec byte layout (then verified empirically by running it) that the
    two pre-existing malformed-`external_senders`-bytes tests in `test/validation/proposal-validation.ts`
    (`new Uint8Array([1, 2])` and `new Uint8Array([1, 2, 3])`, both untouched by this diff) still throw
    `CodecError`/`ValidationError` as expected under the new vector decoder, just via a slightly deeper
    call path (the outer vector length-prefix now parses successfully first, then the *inner*
    single-entry decode fails on the truncated remaining bytes) -- worth knowing that a decode-failure
    test isn't automatically invalidated by wrapping the same payload in an additional length-prefix
    layer, provided the inner decode still runs out of bytes downstream.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 45818 assertions -- 45813 baseline + 5 new), `npm run lint`, and
    `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only the pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts`
    error, unchanged) all pass.
