## 2026-07-17 - US-021
- Implemented: `KeySchedule` (src/key-schedule.ts) no longer has an `epochSecret` field.
  `initializeKeySchedule` still takes `epochSecret` as a parameter (its callers -- `deriveKeySchedule`
  and `client-state.ts`'s external-commit-group-creation path -- each hold their own already-
  disposable copy), but once all nine derived outputs (initSecret/senderDataSecret/encryptionSecret/
  exporterSecret/externalSecret/confirmationKey/membershipKey/resumptionPsk/epochAuthenticator) are
  computed, it calls `epochSecret.fill(0)` before building/returning the `KeySchedule` object. This
  means a later state compromise that captures a `ClientState`/`KeySchedule` can no longer recompute
  the whole epoch's secret hierarchy (including future ratchet-tree segments) from a retained
  `epochSecret`.
- Files changed:
  - `src/key-schedule.ts`: removed `epochSecret` from the `KeySchedule` interface; added the
    `epochSecret.fill(0)` best-effort wipe at the end of `initializeKeySchedule`, after all
    `deriveSecret` calls that need it.
  - `test/key-schedule.ts` (new): for every ciphersuite, generates a random `epochSecret`, calls
    `initializeKeySchedule`, then asserts (a) the returned `KeySchedule` has no `epochSecret`
    property and (b) the original buffer passed in is now all zeros (`notDeepEqual` against a
    pre-call snapshot, plus an explicit `every(b => b === 0)` check).
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new top-level test file.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-021 `passes: true` with interpretation notes.
- Interpretation of acceptance criteria: the story's acceptance criteria also lists "Best-effort
  fill(0) on consumed secrets (joiner/welcome/commit/path secrets and consumed ratchet segments)" --
  broader than the title/description, which are scoped to epoch_secret specifically. Checked every
  other secret that flows through `src/key-schedule.ts` (`joinerSecret`/`pskSecret`/`commitSecret`/
  `initSecret` params, plus the `joinerSecret`/`welcomeSecret` this file returns) and none of them
  are actually dead after use *within this file*: `joinerSecret` in particular is returned to
  callers (`create-commit.ts`, `process-messages.ts`) for welcome-message encryption after
  `deriveKeySchedule`/`initializeEpoch` return, so zeroing it here would break real functionality.
  Only `epochSecret` is locally computed and fully consumed before being discarded, so that's the
  only buffer this story's file-level scope (`src/key-schedule.ts`) can safely wipe. The broader
  "path/node secrets" and "ratchet segments" half of that same acceptance-criteria line is the
  literal, explicit scope of US-028 (already present in `specs/prd.json` targeting
  `src/update-path.ts`, `src/path-secrets.ts`, `src/private-key-path.ts`, `src/secret-tree.ts`,
  `src/client-state.ts`) -- left untouched here to avoid preempting that story.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - `test/index.ts` also has a small set of top-level (non-scenario, non-codec, non-test-vector)
    per-file tests registered directly (`base64.ts`, `ciphersuite.ts`, `extensions-equal.ts`,
    `transcript-hash-epoch0.ts`) near the top of the import list -- useful pattern for a focused
    unit test on a single `src/` module/function rather than a full multi-party scenario. Added
