## 2026-07-17 - US-022 (BLOCKED -- passes left false)
- Attempted: set `lowS: true` on both `sign` and `verify` for P256/P384/P521 in
  `src/crypto/implementation/default/make-noble-signature-impl.ts`, exactly per the acceptance
  criteria, with a TDD-first test (`test/crypto/signature.ts`) that signs a fresh message per curve,
  asserts `!Signature.fromBytes(sig, 'der').hasHighS()` (canonical sign), then constructs the
  mathematically-equivalent malleated counterpart (`new Signature(r, CURVE_ORDER - s)`) and asserts
  it does NOT verify. Confirmed genuine RED pre-fix (both new assertions failed, all 3 curves;
  `git stash push -- src/crypto/implementation/default/make-noble-signature-impl.ts`, single-file
  esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns) and genuine GREEN post-fix, `npm run lint` clean,
  `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` unaffected (only the pre-existing documented key-schedule.ts error).
- Then ran the full suite as the final gate (rule 4) and hit a real, reproducible failure: an
  uncaught `CryptoVerificationError: Signature invalid` in `test/test-vectors/message-protection.ts`
  ("message-protection test vectors 1", the `publicCommit` check), crashing the whole run.
- Root-caused it precisely (see `/tmp`-style probe: decode `data.commit_pub` via
  `decodeMlsMessage`/`src/message.ts`, extract `publicMessage.auth.signature`, parse with
  `@noble/curves`'s `Signature.fromBytes(bytes, 'der')`, call `.hasHighS()`): the *official* RFC 9420
  `test_vectors/message-protection.json` vector for `cipher_suite: 2` (P-256) contains a legitimate
  but **non-canonical (high-S)** commit signature, produced by whatever reference implementation
  generated that vector. It is not this repo's own signature -- it's externally-supplied ground-truth
  wire data decoded and verified, not created by our `sign()`. Confirmed via `git stash` that this
  vector passes today (all 84 message-protection assertions green) and only breaks once verify
  enforces `lowS: true`.
- Confirmed via `SECURITY-AUDIT.md:398-400` that the audit itself calls the current `lowS: false`
  behavior "Conformant" and phrases the recommendation as "Consider `lowS: true`" -- i.e. RFC 9420
  does not mandate canonical ECDSA signatures, so strict verify-side rejection is a real, deliberate
  deviation from spec conformance, not a bug fix. Because ECDSA malleability means `(r, s)` and
  `(r, n-s)` are both mathematically valid signatures for the same message, there is no way for a
  strict verifier to distinguish "an attacker flipped this in transit" from "the original honest
  signer's ECDSA nonce happened to produce a high-S value" (~50% of all naturally-generated ECDSA
  signatures, by construction) -- these are the same bit pattern. So enforcing `lowS: true` on verify
  necessarily and unavoidably rejects some fraction of legitimately-signed messages from any peer
  (including the official RFC reference implementation) that doesn't also canonicalize on sign. This
  is not specific to this one vector -- every ECDSA-ciphersuite commit/proposal signature in the
  official test-vector corpus has the same ~50% chance of hitting this, so the regression is systemic,
  not an isolated fluke worth carving out an exception for.
- Decision: did NOT apply the fix. Reverted the working tree to clean
  (`git checkout -- src/crypto/implementation/default/make-noble-signature-impl.ts
  test/crypto/signature.ts`) rather than commit a change that breaks a genuine, currently-passing
  RFC spec-conformance test, or weaken/carve an exception into that test to force green -- both are
  explicitly against the session's integrity rules. `specs/prd.json` left with US-022 `passes: false`.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - This is the first story in this project to hit a real, load-bearing conflict between an
    acceptance criterion and an existing passing spec-conformance test, rather than a
    straightforward implementation gap. Don't try to force a resolution by editing test data,
    skipping the specific vector, or writing a narrower assertion -- that's the "weaken tests to
    force green" trap. If a future session picks this back up, the options actually on the table
    are: (a) accept the interop cost and implement literally as specified (breaks the P-256/P-384/
    P-521 message-protection RFC vectors, which would then need honest acknowledgment/adjustment
    with maintainer sign-off, not silent test-weakening); (b) sign-only partial mitigation (`lowS:
    true` on `sign`, leave `verify` lenient) -- zero regression risk since a low-S signature is
    always a valid signature, but does NOT close the actual vulnerability (an attacker can still
    malleate a signature in transit and have it accepted, still producing two valid ProposalRefs for
    logically the same proposal) so it wouldn't honestly satisfy this story either; (c) the
    architecturally complete fix with zero interop cost: keep `verify` lenient (accepts both low-S
    and high-S, preserving RFC conformance), but canonicalize the signature to its low-S form
    immediately after successful verification, before it's used anywhere a byte-identical encoding
    matters for uniqueness -- specifically before `makeProposalRef` (`src/authenticated-content.ts:92`,
    which hashes `encodeAuthenticatedContent(proposal)` including the raw `auth.signature` bytes) and
    anywhere else `encodeAuthenticatedContent`'s output is used as a content-addressed identifier.
    This closes the "two valid ProposalRefs" threat model exactly as described without rejecting any
    spec-conformant message, but it's a bigger architectural change spanning more files than this
    story's stated scope (`make-noble-signature-impl.ts` only) -- would need its own story/scope
    if pursued.
  - `decodeMlsMessage` lives in `src/message.ts` (not `src/message-framing.js`, which doesn't exist);
    `publicMessage.auth.signature` is where a `PublicMessage`'s raw DER signature bytes live post-
    decode. `@noble/curves`'s `Signature.fromBytes(bytes, 'der')` / `.hasHighS()` / `curve.Point.Fn.ORDER`
    are the tools for constructing/inspecting a malleated counterpart signature in a test (see the
    reverted `test/crypto/signature.ts` draft in this entry's investigation, not currently in the tree).
  - No commit made this session (nothing was accepted); working tree confirmed clean via `git status`
    at the end.
