## 2026-07-17 (third pass) - US-022 (still BLOCKED -- passes left false)
- This session's brief explicitly asked to question the prior two sessions' assumptions and try a
  different approach rather than just re-running the same experiment a third time. Used
  `superpowers:systematic-debugging` and went one level deeper than either prior session: instead of
  only patch-and-observe, independently re-derived the root cause from first principles and from the
  `@noble/curves` library source itself, then broadened the empirical check beyond the single
  previously-identified vector. Conclusion is unchanged but now substantially better evidenced, and
  the blast radius is larger than previously documented.
- New evidence gathered this session:
  1. **Algebraic proof the conflict is unavoidable, not an implementation gap.** For any valid ECDSA
     signature `(r, s)` on curve order `n`, `(r, n-s)` is also a valid signature for the exact same
     message and key: negating `s` negates `u1 = h*s^-1 mod n` and `u2 = r*s^-1 mod n`, so the
     recovered point `R' = u1*G + u2*Q` becomes `-R`, and on a short-Weierstrass curve `-R` has the
     same x-coordinate as `R` (point negation only flips `y`). Since verification only checks `R.x mod
     n == r`, both signatures pass. A `verify()` function that only ever sees the final `(r, s)` wire
     bytes has no way to distinguish "attacker flipped an honest low-S signature into its high-S
     malleated twin in transit" from "the original signer's nonce happened to produce high-S and
     never canonicalized it" -- these are the same bit pattern by construction (~50% of freshly
     generated ECDSA signatures are naturally high-S). This is a property of ECDSA itself, not of this
     codebase or this library.
  2. **Confirmed directly in the installed `@noble/curves` source** (`node_modules/@noble/curves/abstract/weierstrass.js`,
     `verify()`, ~line 1374): `if (lowS && sig.hasHighS()) return false;` -- an unconditional, non-
     configurable hard reject with no "verify but tell me the canonical form" mode. There is no
     library-level escape hatch; `lowS: true` on `verify()` can only ever mean "reject every high-S
     signature," full stop.
  3. **Broadened the vector sweep beyond the single P-256 commit vector the prior sessions found.**
     Wrote a standalone probe (decoded every ECDSA-suite `proposal_pub`/`commit_pub` in
     `test_vectors/message-protection.json` via this repo's own `decodeMlsMessage`, then checked
     `Signature.fromBytes(sig, 'der').hasHighS()` per curve) and found the problem is systemic across
     **all three** ECDSA ciphersuites in the vector file, not just the one previously identified case:
     - suite 2 (P256): `commit_pub` is high-S (`proposal_pub` is low-S)
     - suite 5 (P521): **both** `proposal_pub` and `commit_pub` are high-S
     - suite 7 (P384): `proposal_pub` is high-S (`commit_pub` is low-S)
     So a strict `lowS: true` verify would break message-protection RFC-vector coverage for P-256,
     P-384, and P-521 alike -- this is not a one-vector fluke worth a narrow carve-out, it's the
     expected ~50/50 outcome of an external reference implementation that (like this codebase today)
     doesn't canonicalize on sign, sampled across three independent curves.
  4. **Confirmed vector provenance.** `test_vectors/*.json` (message-protection.json,
     crypto-basics.json, tree-math.json, welcome.json, etc.) are the standard file names from the
     MLS working group's published interoperability test-vector corpus, added in one bulk commit
     (`00a32e0`, "test with tapzero, tests pass") together with the test harness that consumes them --
     there is no generator script in this repo that produced them. They are external ground truth,
     not a fixture this project has license to regenerate with canonical signatures.
  5. **Re-ran the literal patch live, one more time.** Set `lowS: true` on all six P256/P384/P521
     sign/verify call sites, ran `test/test-vectors/message-protection.ts` alone via the single-file
     esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns: identical crash to both prior sessions --
     `CryptoVerificationError: Signature invalid` thrown from `unprotectPublicMessage`, at
     `publicCommit`, on "message-protection test vectors 1" (suite 2 / P-256) -- matching exactly what
     bullet 3 above predicts (vector 1's `commit_pub` is the high-S one). Reverted immediately
     (`git checkout --`); confirmed `git status` clean before writing this entry.
- Decision: unchanged from the prior two sessions -- left `specs/prd.json` US-022 `passes: false`.
  Did not implement literal option (a) (real, now-confirmed-systemic RFC-vector regression, would
  fail this story's own "Tests pass" acceptance line -- rule 6 INTEGRITY forbids marking this done
  while a real test is failing). Did not unilaterally implement or rescope to option (c) (lenient
  verify + sign-side canonicalization + post-verify `ProposalRef` canonicalization) either, since that
  reinterprets the acceptance criteria to force a green result -- explicitly called out as off-limits
  in the prior entry, and this session found no new information that changes that judgment call, only
  stronger confirmation of *why* it's the right call.
- **Recommendation for a human maintainer** (not something this session is authorized to do
  unilaterally): this is now three consecutive sessions independently reaching the identical
  conclusion via three different verification methods (patch-and-observe twice, then source+data
  analysis). Further autonomous attempts at the literal acceptance criteria will keep reproducing this
  exact result and burn sessions for zero new information. Concretely, either:
  - (a) Explicitly accept the RFC 9420 message-protection vector regression for P-256/P-384/P-521 and
    say so in `specs/prd.json`, at which point a future session can implement the literal fix and
    handle the now-expected vector failures honestly (e.g. an explicitly-documented, narrowly-scoped
    exception for those specific known-non-canonical reference signatures, not a silent skip); or
