## 2026-07-17 - US-024
- Fixed two defense-in-depth codec issues:
  1. `decoderWithPadding` in src/private-message.ts used
     `paddingBytes.every((byte) => byte === 0)`, which short-circuits on the
     first non-zero byte (early exit -- a timing side channel on padding
     content). Replaced with a manual loop that OR-accumulates every byte
     into a `diff` variable with no early return, so the scan always visits
     every padding byte regardless of where a non-zero byte occurs.
  2. `decodeVarLenType` in src/codec/variable-length.ts's inner
     `while (cursor < totalBytes.length)` loop called the item decoder and
     advanced `cursor` by the returned `len`, but never checked `len > 0`.
     An item decoder that legitimately or maliciously returns `[value, 0]`
     (consumes zero bytes) causes `cursor` to never advance -- an infinite
     loop growing `result` without bound. Added `if (len === 0) return
     undefined` immediately after unpacking `[value, len]`.
- Files changed: src/private-message.ts, src/codec/variable-length.ts,
  test/codec/var-length-encoding.ts.
- Tests: added `varLength decodeVarLenType rejects an item decoder that
  consumes zero bytes instead of hanging` in
  test/codec/var-length-encoding.ts, using a stub decoder that always
  returns `[0, 0]` -- confirmed RED (uncaught `RangeError: Invalid array
  length` from unbounded `result.push` -- Node's practical manifestation of
  what would otherwise hang forever) before the fix, GREEN after. Existing
  padding tests in test/codec/padding.ts already cover non-zero-padding
  rejection at various positions and continued to pass unchanged; a
  constant-time bitwise scan is not independently unit-testable via timing
  assertions in this harness, so no new test was added for that half --
  correctness is covered by the existing padding tests.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - `decodeVarLenType` (src/codec/variable-length.ts) is the generic
    "decode array of T" codec used throughout this codebase's vector
    types. Any per-item `Decoder<T>` that can return a zero-length
    consumption (offset delta of 0) will now correctly fail the whole
    array decode instead of hanging -- worth remembering if a future story
    adds a new `Decoder<T>` that might legitimately encode a
    zero-length item (none currently do; all real decoders in this repo
    consume at least a length-prefix byte).
  - To force a RED test for a hang-shaped bug without an actual infinite
    loop, use a stub decoder that returns a constant `[value, 0]` -- Node
    hits an `Array` length ceiling on unbounded `.push()` and throws
    `RangeError: Invalid array length` fast, which is fine as the pre-fix
    "proof of bug" signal (a real timeout isn't needed).
