## 2026-07-17 - US-025
- Implemented: hardened both halves of L5/L6.
  - L6 (real, reachable bug): `applyUpdatePath` (src/update-path.ts) only compared incoming
    UpdatePath node public keys against existing **parent** node keys in the tree
    (`treeNode?.nodeType === 'parent' ? constantTimeEqual(...) : false`), missing two RFC 9420
    SS7.6 requirements: (a) new keys must also be distinct from every existing **leaf** key, and
    (b) new keys must be distinct from each other **within the UpdatePath itself**. Both checks
    are now enforced, each throwing its own `ValidationError` with a distinct message.
  - L5 (hardening, no true RED achievable): `parentHashCoverage`'s bottom-up walk
    (src/parent-hash.ts) had a `// skip blank nodes / if (currentNode === undefined) { continue }`
    branch that never advanced `currentIndex`, i.e. a hang if ever reached. Replaced the bare
    `continue` with `currentIndex = findFirstNonBlankAncestor(tree, currentIndex); continue` so
    the loop provably terminates (monotonic progress toward the root) even in this branch.
- Files changed:
  - `src/update-path.ts`: `applyUpdatePath`'s existing-key check now builds `existingKey` from
    either `treeNode.parent.hpkePublicKey` or `treeNode.leaf.hpkePublicKey` depending on
    `nodeType` (previously parent-only); added a second check,
    `path.nodes.some((node, i) => path.nodes.some((other, j) => i !== j && constantTimeEqual(...)))`,
    thrown as `'Public keys in the UpdatePath must be distinct from each other'`.
  - `src/parent-hash.ts`: `parentHashCoverage`'s blank-node branch now re-derives `currentIndex`
    via the already-imported `findFirstNonBlankAncestor` instead of looping in place.
  - `test/validation/update-path-key-uniqueness.ts` (was already present, untracked, from a prior
    stalled session -- see the recurring "found already drafted" Codebase Patterns bullet, though
    this is the first time that pattern applied to a *test-only* draft with no matching `src/`
    fix present). Reviewed and fixed two real problems in the draft before trusting it (see
    Learnings), rewired `t.rejects(...)` calls (not a tapzero API -- this codebase's `throws`
    signature is `(fn, expected?:RegExp, message?)`, no async-matcher form) to manual
    try/catch + `t.ok(caught instanceof ValidationError && caught.message === '...')`, and removed
    two unused imports (`joinGroup`, `emptyPskIndex`) that failed lint.
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new validation test (alphabetically after
    `unmerged-leaves-validation.js`).
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-025 `passes: true` with notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - The drafted test's original assertions (`t.ok(caught instanceof ValidationError, ...)`) were a
    **false-positive test**: tampering a path node's `hpkePublicKey` also perturbs the recomputed
    parent-hash chain later in `applyUpdatePath` (the final
    `constantTimeEqual(leafParentHash[0], path.leafNode.parentHash)` check), which throws its own
    unrelated `ValidationError('Parent hash did not match the UpdatePath')` regardless of whether
    the missing collision/duplicate check exists. Verified this empirically with a standalone debug
    script calling `applyUpdatePath` directly against the pre-fix source and printing the caught
    error's exact message -- pre-fix, both scenarios threw the parent-hash-mismatch message, not a
    collision-specific one. Fixed by asserting on the exact expected error `message` string (not
    just `instanceof ValidationError`), which correctly turns RED pre-fix (38/57 assertions fail,
    all on message mismatch) and GREEN post-fix (57/57). **General lesson: when a fix adds an
    early-exit validation check ahead of other checks that can independently throw the same error
    type for a different reason, `instanceof SomeError` alone is not sufficient to prove the new
    check fired -- assert on the specific message/discriminant, or otherwise structure the test so
    only the new check's failure mode is reachable.**
  - L5's fix is (like US-003/US-012, both referenced in Codebase Patterns) a hardening-only change
    with no achievable RED-before/GREEN-after integration test: proved analytically (not just by
    trial) that `parentHashCoverage`'s `currentIndex` is *always* either the initial (checked
    non-blank) leaf position or a `parentHashNodeIndex` returned by `calculateParentHash`, which
    itself is always either a genuinely non-blank strict ancestor (found via
    `findFirstNonBlankAncestor`'s `traverseToRoot` callback, which only fires on non-undefined
    nodes) or the tree root -- and if the root is blank, the `while (currentIndex !== rootIndex)`
    loop condition is already false by the time that value is assigned, so `tree[currentIndex]` is
    never dereferenced while blank. This holds for *any* well-typed `RatchetTree` array, not just
    protocol-derived ones (it's a property of the `calculateParentHash`/`findFirstNonBlankAncestor`
    contract, independent of how the tree was built), and this codebase has no mocking/spy library
    to force the internal call chain into an otherwise-unreachable state. Applied the fix anyway
    (defense-in-depth per the story's explicit framing: "never spin on a blank node") and verified
    no regression via the existing `test/validation/parent-hash-resolution.ts` and
    `test/scenario/add-with-path.ts` (both exercise blank-intermediate-ancestor skipping through
    `calculateParentHash` in normal operation) plus the full suite.
  - `findFirstNonBlankAncestor(tree, nodeIndex)` (src/ratchet-tree.ts) works for *either* a leaf or
    a parent `nodeIndex` despite its internal `nodeToLeafIndex(nodeIndex)` -> `traverseToRoot` ->
    `leafToNodeIndex(leafIndex)` round trip looking leaf-specific: `nodeToLeafIndex` and
    `leafToNodeIndex` are exact inverses for any integer (`(n/2)*2 === n`), including odd/parent
    indices, so the round trip is a no-op and `traverseToRoot` effectively starts walking
    strictly-upward from whatever `nodeIndex` was passed in, regardless of parity.
  - Verified TDD properly on the reachable half (L6): `git stash push -- src/update-path.ts` (kept
    the test file), reran via the single-file esbuild-bundle recipe from Codebase Patterns -- got
    38/57 assertions failing pre-fix (all on message mismatch, confirming both scenarios throw the
    wrong/unrelated error pre-fix as described above). `git stash pop` restored the fix; 57/57 pass.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 46075 assertions -- 46018 baseline + 57 new), `npm run lint`, and
    `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only the pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts`
    error, unchanged) all pass.
