    and loops over the whole array instead of `pskIds.find(...)`'s single match; the resumption
    continuity checks (epoch match, groupId match, epoch===1 on join, reinit-specific checks) are
    unchanged in content, just now applied to every qualifying PSK instead of at most one.
  - `src/presharedkey.ts`: `updatePskSecret` throws `ValidationError` if `index > 0xffff ||
    count > 0xffff` before calling `expandWithLabel`.
  - `src/psk-index.ts`: `accumulatePskSecret`'s reduce body throws `ValidationError` if
    `cur.pskNonce.length !== cs.kdf.size` before calling `pskSearch.findPsk(cur)`.
  - `test/validation/psk-field-validation.ts` (new): four scenarios x all ciphersuites --
    (1) an application-usage resumption PSK is accepted by `joinGroup` with no `resumingFromState`
    passed (mirrors external-PSK handling); (2) a commit carrying two resumption PSK proposals
    (good epoch first, wrong epoch second) is rejected -- this is the regression check for the
    "only the first PSK was validated" bug, since a `.find()`-based implementation would validate
    only the first (good) one and never notice the second (bad) one; (3) `accumulatePskSecret`
    rejects a 1-byte `pskNonce` and accepts a `cs.kdf.size`-byte one; (4) `updatePskSecret` rejects
    `index`/`count` of `0x10000` and accepts `0xffff`.
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new validation test file.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-027 `passes: true` with implementation notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - This is another instance of the "working tree already contains a fully-drafted fix at session
    start" pattern already documented in Codebase Patterns (US-005/006/007/011/012/015/016/017/018/026)
    -- `git status` at session start showed `src/client-state.ts`, `src/presharedkey.ts`,
    `src/psk-index.ts`, and `test/index.ts` modified plus an untracked `test/validation/psk-field-validation.ts`,
    all directly matching this story's acceptance criteria. Reviewed against RFC 9420 SS12.4.3
    (resumption PSK usages) and SS7.7 (KDF.Nh-length nonces) before trusting it, rather than
    reimplementing from scratch.
  - RED/GREEN verification note: `git stash` does NOT touch untracked files by default, so
    stashing the three modified `src/*.ts` files (leaving the untracked new test file in place)
    produces a genuine pre-fix run without needing `-u` or any extra bookkeeping -- ran the new
    test bundle against that stashed state first (threw `ValidationError('No prior state passed
    for resumption')` on the application-usage-PSK case, confirming real RED), then `git stash pop`
    and reran for GREEN (133/133 new assertions).
  - `PreSharedKeyIdResumption` (`PSKInfoResumption & PSKNonce`, exported from `src/presharedkey.ts`)
    is the correct type to narrow `PreSharedKeyID` to when you need the resumption-specific fields
    (`usage`, `pskGroupId`, `pskEpoch`) via a TypeScript type-guard filter -- useful whenever future
    work needs to distinguish resumption PSKs from external ones at the type level rather than just
    via a runtime `psktype` check.
  - `src/resumption.ts`'s `makeResumptionPsk(state, usage, cs)` is the existing helper for
    constructing a real resumption `PreSharedKeyID` + secret pair in tests (used by
    `reinitCreateNewGroup`/`branchGroup` in production code too) -- reuse it rather than
    hand-rolling a resumption PSK object when a test needs one with a *correct* nonce/secret
    relationship; only hand-roll the "bad" PSK id (e.g. wrong epoch) since its whole point is to
    be rejected.
