## 2026-07-17 - US-028

- Implemented: forward-secrecy key-material reduction per L10/L11/L12 -- (1) historical receiver
  data snapshots now strip each leaf's handshake ratchet (zeroized, replaced with an empty
  placeholder) while keeping the application ratchet usable, since a commit/proposal from a former
  epoch is rejected outright regardless of decryptability; (2) `createSecretTree` no longer derives
  or retains ratchet roots for internal (non-leaf) `SecretTree` node indices, since nothing in this
  codebase ever ratchets a message using a non-leaf index; (3) path/node secrets in
  `update-path.ts`/`path-secrets.ts`/`private-key-path.ts`/`create-commit.ts`/`process-messages.ts`/
  `client-state.ts` are `fill(0)`-zeroized once every real consumer (deriving the commit secret,
  deriving retained HPKE private keys, building a new joiner's Welcome) has read them.
- This session's REASONING note said the task "stalled once already." Found this story's
  implementation already drafted, uncommitted, in the working tree at session start (`src/client-
  state.ts`, `src/create-commit.ts`, `src/path-secrets.ts`, `src/private-key-path.ts`, `src/process-
  messages.ts`, `src/secret-tree.ts`, `src/update-path.ts`, `test/index.ts` modified; `test/
  validation/key-material-retention.ts` untracked) -- the same recurring pattern documented across
  many earlier stories in Codebase Patterns. Per that pattern's own guidance (and per
  systematic-debugging), reviewed the draft against every acceptance criterion line-by-line and
  traced every zeroized buffer to its last real consumer, rather than assuming a "looks complete and
  its own test passes" draft was correct -- this is what surfaced the regression below, which a
  shallower review (or blind trust in the draft's already-passing test) would have missed and shipped.
- **Found and fixed a real regression in the draft**: `createCommit` (src/create-commit.ts) computed
  `commitSecret` from `pathSecrets`, then immediately called `zeroPathSecretsArray(pathSecrets)` --
  but `pathSecrets` (the same array, by reference) is also passed into `createWelcome` (called ~50
  lines later) to build each newly-added member's `EncryptedGroupSecrets` via
  `createEncryptedGroupSecrets`'s `pathSecret?.secret` read. Since the zero call ran before that
  second read, ANY commit that both adds a member and requires an UpdatePath (e.g. add+remove in the
  same commit, or any add commit where `needsUpdatePath` is otherwise true) handed the new joiner an
  all-zero `pathSecret` in their Welcome instead of the real one -- the new joiner would derive a
  private key for the shared ancestor node that does not match what the committer's tree actually
  contains, silently breaking their ability to process future commits/messages relying on that
  secret. Confirmed via a direct probe comparing the committer's and new joiner's exported private
  key bytes for their shared ancestor node (must be byte-identical; were not, pre-fix) rather than
  trusting the draft's own HPKE-roundtrip-style assertion. Fixed by moving
  `zeroPathSecretsArray(pathSecrets)` to run after `createWelcome` returns, i.e. after every real
  consumer of `pathSecrets` has read it. Checked `joinGroupExternal`'s analogous zero call (same
  file) for the same class of bug -- safe as drafted, since external commits build no Welcome and
  `pathSecrets` has no reader after that point.
- **Found and fixed a second issue**: the draft's own regression test for the bug above
  (`welcomeCarriesRealPathSecret` in the untracked `test/validation/key-material-retention.ts`)
  never actually caught it, because that test file's `skippable(error)` helper was broadened beyond
  this codebase's established `NotSupportedError`/`DependencyError`-only convention (used identically
  in every other `test/scenario/*.ts` file) to also catch `CryptoError`/`DeriveKeyPairError`/message-
  substring checks -- and the premature-zeroing bug's HPKE round-trip probe fails with exactly a
  `CryptoError` (`OpenError: invalid tag` / `OpenError: ... operation-specific reason`), so the
  broadened catch logged it as a per-ciphersuite "skip" instead of a failure, across all 19
  ciphersuites, both before and after the src fix. Tightened `skippable()` back to the established
  two-error convention, which made the real assertion execute; reran and confirmed a genuine RED
  (uncaught `CryptoError` crashing the run) against a manually-reintroduced copy of the original bug,
  and genuine GREEN with the fix restored.
- Also fixed a TypeScript regression the draft introduced: in `process-messages.ts`'s
  `processPrivateMessage`, moving the former-epoch rejection check earlier (from
  `result.content.content.contentType === 'application'`, checked after decrypting, to
  `pm.contentType !== 'application'`, checked before decrypting -- necessary now that a historical
  epoch's handshake ratchet is actually gone, not just discarded-after-use) broke TypeScript's
  discriminated-union narrowing on the later `result.content.content.applicationData` access, since
  TS cannot narrow one variable's type from a check against a differently-typed/named variable.
  Confirmed `pm.contentType` and `result.content.content.contentType` must always agree (`content_type`
  is part of `PrivateContentAAD`, so it's authenticated as associated data by the AEAD tag in both
  `protect`/`unprotectPrivateMessage` -- tampering it fails decryption regardless of this check's
  position) before fixing. Fix: added an explicit `if (result.content.content.contentType !==
  'application') throw new InternalError(...)` guard immediately before the return, which both
  restores narrowing and serves as a genuine defense-in-depth invariant check.
- Files changed:
  - `src/client-state.ts`: new `deriveUpdatedPrivateKeyPath` helper (extracted from `joinGroup`'s
    inline ternary) zeroizes the locally-derived `PathSecrets` record from `pathToRoot` once
    `toPrivateKeyPath` has produced the retained `PrivateKeyPath`; `addHistoricalReceiverData` wraps
    `state.secretTree` in the new `stripHandshakeRatchets`.
  - `src/create-commit.ts`: `zeroPathSecretsArray` (imported from `update-path.js`) call in
    `createCommit` moved to after `createWelcome` (the fix); `joinGroupExternal`'s call left as
    drafted (verified safe).
  - `src/path-secrets.ts`: new `zeroPathSecrets(pathSecrets:PathSecrets)` utility.
  - `src/private-key-path.ts`: `toPrivateKeyPath` zeroizes its locally-derived `nodeSecret` (the
    HKDF 'node'-label output) immediately after deriving the HPKE keypair from it -- distinct buffer
    from both the input `pathSecret` and the exported private key, so this is safe.
  - `src/process-messages.ts`: former-epoch handshake-content pre-check (with the `InternalError`
    narrowing-guard fix); `updatePrivateKeyPath` derives `commitSecret` from `lastSecret` *before*
    calling `zeroPathSecrets(pathSecrets)` (the same buffer as `pathSecrets`' final entry).
  - `src/secret-tree.ts`: `SecretTree` is now `(SecretTreeNode | undefined)[]`; `createSecretTree`
    only derives ratchet roots for leaf indices (`isLeaf(toNodeIndex(index))`), leaving internal
    nodes `undefined`; new `stripHandshakeRatchets(tree)` zeroizes+empties each leaf's handshake
    ratchet while preserving its `application` ratchet object by reference (safe: ratchet-consuming
    functions are non-mutating/functional, always returning a new tree rather than mutating node
    objects in place, so sharing the `application` reference between a live and a historical-
    snapshot tree cannot corrupt either). Verified every `SecretTree` index read in `src/`
    (`message-protection.ts`'s `protect`/`unprotectPrivateMessage`) goes through
    `leafToNodeIndex(toLeafIndex(...))`, never a raw/internal node index, so the new `undefined`
    entries for internal nodes are never dereferenced.
  - `src/update-path.ts`: new `zeroPathSecretsArray(pathSecrets:PathSecret[])` utility;
    `createUpdatePath` zeroizes its `leafNodeSecret` after deriving the leaf HPKE keypair;
    `applyInitialTreeUpdate` zeroizes each iteration's `nextNodeSecret` after deriving that node's
    HPKE keypair (distinct buffer from the retained `nextPathSecret`, so safe).
  - `test/validation/key-material-retention.ts` (new, drafted then hardened this session): four
    tests x every ciphersuite -- internal `SecretTree` nodes are never retained; historical receiver
    data strips the handshake ratchet but keeps `application` usable; path secrets can be zeroized
    via `zeroPathSecretsArray`/`zeroPathSecrets` without corrupting already-derived private keys or
    breaking a real commit/decrypt flow; and (the one that caught the regression once `skippable()`
    was tightened) a Welcome from a commit that both adds a member and requires an UpdatePath carries
    the real, non-zeroized path secret -- verified via both an HPKE round-trip probe through the
    tree's real ancestor public key and a direct `derivedPrivateKeyBytes !== undefined` check. Also
    fixed an unrelated `prefer-const` lint error on `bobGroup` (never reassigned).
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new validation test (already present in the draft).
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-028 `passes: true` with notes summarizing the two bugs found/fixed.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - See the two new Codebase Patterns bullets added above: (1) trace a zeroized shared buffer to
    its *last* real consumer, not just the read immediately before the zero call -- non-adjacent
    reads several function calls away are easy to miss; (2) a scenario/validation test's
    `skippable()` catch-all should match this project's established `NotSupportedError`/
    `DependencyError`-only convention -- a broadened one can silently swallow the exact regression
    the test was written to catch.
  - Verified TDD properly for the `createCommit` fix: manually reintroduced the original (buggy)
    zero-call ordering, reran the tightened test -- got an uncaught `CryptoError: OpenError: The
    operation failed for an operation-specific reason` crashing the whole run (a real RED, not a
    silent skip), confirming the tightened `skippable()` now actually exercises this path. Restored
    the fix; full 323/323 assertions in the file passed (GREEN).
  - `pathToRoot` (src/path-secrets.ts)'s returned `PathSecrets` record's *first* entry (keyed by the
    `nodeIndex` argument) is literally the same `Uint8Array` object as the `pathSecret` argument
    passed in, not a copy -- so `zeroPathSecrets` on that record's output also zeroizes the caller's
    original buffer. This is exploited intentionally by `client-state.ts`'s new
    `deriveUpdatedPrivateKeyPath` (zeroizing `groupSecrets.pathSecret` in `joinGroup` once it's no
    longer needed), but it's a sharp edge worth knowing about before reusing `pathToRoot` elsewhere.
  - `pathSecretsAlongFilteredPath` (src/path-secrets.ts)'s returned `lastSecret` is similarly the
    same object as `pathSecrets`' final entry (by construction of the loop that builds both) --
    this is *why* `process-messages.ts`'s `updatePrivateKeyPath` must derive `commitSecret` from
    `lastSecret` before calling `zeroPathSecrets(pathSecrets)`, not after.
  - `@hpke/common`'s `HpkeError` base class sets `this.name = this.constructor.name`, so a real HPKE
    library error's `.name` is its specific subclass name (e.g. `'OpenError'`), never `'CryptoError'`
    -- when this codebase's own `CryptoError` (src/mls-error.ts) wraps one, the resulting `.name` is
    `'CryptoError'` and the *message* is what carries the original error's `name: message` string
    (e.g. `"OpenError: invalid tag"`). Useful to know when deciding whether an error-matching
    condition in a test is actually narrow (matching this codebase's own error classes) or
    accidentally broad (matching by message substring against an underlying library's error text).
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 46569 assertions -- 46246 baseline + 323 new), `npm run lint`, and
    `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` (only the pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts`
    error, unchanged) all pass.
