## 2026-07-17 - US-029

- Implemented: `proposeExternal` (src/external-proposal.ts) now validates `proposal.proposalType`
  against an allow-list (`add`, `remove`, `psk`, `reinit`, `group_context_extensions`) before
  building the message, throwing `UsageError` for `update`, `external_init`, or any custom
  (numeric) proposal type. Per RFC 9420 Table 3 (proposal types permitted by external senders),
  Update and ExternalInit are sender-restricted and were previously only rejected on the receiver
  side (in `processPublicMessage`, further downstream) -- an API consumer could still successfully
  *construct* and sign a non-conformant external Update/ExternalInit message even though every
  compliant receiver would reject it. This closes that gap at the point of construction.
- Files changed:
  - `src/external-proposal.ts`: added `proposalTypesPermittedForExternalSenders` (a `Set<string>`)
    and a guard at the top of `proposeExternal` that throws `UsageError` when
    `proposal.proposalType` is not a string in that set (custom/numeric proposal types are
    `number`, not `string`, so `typeof proposal.proposalType !== 'string'` is checked first --
    `Set<string>.has(someNumber)` is a TS type error, not just a false-negative).
  - `test/scenario/external-proposal-restricted-types.ts` (new): asserts `proposeExternal` throws
    `UsageError` when given an `update` or `external_init` proposal, across all ciphersuites.
  - `test/scenario/external-sender-policy.ts`: updated `externalUpdateRejected` -- it previously
    called `proposeExternal` to build an external Update message and asserted `ValidationError`
    from a *later* `processPublicMessage` call; with the new construction-time guard,
    `proposeExternal` itself now throws first, so the test now asserts `UsageError` from the
    `proposeExternal` call directly. The receiver-side `ValidationError` rejection this test used
    to exercise still exists in the codebase (a hand-crafted/bypassing-`proposeExternal` message
    would still hit it) but is no longer reachable through this particular test's code path since
    it goes through `proposeExternal`.
  - `test/index.ts`: registered the new scenario test file.
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-029 `passes: true` with implementation notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - `Proposal.proposalType` (src/proposal.ts) is typed `string | number` (custom/unknown proposal
    types decode to a raw `number`), not a closed string union -- any allow-list/deny-list check
    against it needs an explicit `typeof proposal.proposalType === 'string'` narrow before doing
    `Set<string>.has(...)` or a string-literal switch, or `tsc --noEmit` fails with "Argument of
    type 'number | \"add\" | ...' is not assignable to parameter of type 'string'".
  - When a construction-time (sender-side/API) guard is added for something previously only
    validated receiver-side, grep every existing test that builds the now-restricted case via the
    public constructor function (not just tests literally named for the new behavior) --
    `test/scenario/external-sender-policy.ts`'s pre-existing `externalUpdateRejected` test used
    `proposeExternal` to build its fixture and broke immediately (uncaught throw, not a silent
    pass) once the new guard shipped, because the rejection point moved earlier in the same call
    chain the test already exercised.
  - Verified TDD properly: ran the new restricted-types test against pre-fix code and confirmed
    both assertions (`not ok ... should throw`) failed with `pass 0 / fail 38` (both Update and
    ExternalInit constructed successfully); after the fix, `pass 76 / fail 0`.
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 46645 assertions -- 46569 baseline + 76 new) and `npm run lint` both
    pass. `npx tsc --noEmit -p .` has only the pre-existing, documented
    `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` error, unchanged from before this session's change.
