## 2026-07-17 - US-030
- Implemented: resolved the L14 npm-audit finding (SECURITY-AUDIT.md: "3 high-severity advisories
  in devDependencies only, `trim` via `tap-out`/`tap-spec`, ReDoS"). Removed the unused `tap-spec`
  devDependency from `package.json`. `npm audit` now reports 0 vulnerabilities at every severity
  (info/low/moderate/high/critical), down from the 3 high-severity advisories the finding
  describes. This project's actual test-runner tooling is the scoped `@substrate-system/tapout`
  package (plus `@substrate-system/tapzero`) -- a different package from the unscoped, vulnerable
  `tap-out`/`tap-spec` chain -- so `tap-spec` was dead weight, not wired into any npm script,
  source file, or doc outside of `SECURITY-AUDIT.md` and `specs/prd.json`'s own description of the
  finding.
- Found this story's fix already made, uncommitted, in the working tree at session start: `git
  status`/`git diff` showed only a one-line removal of `"tap-spec": "^5.0.0"` from `package.json`,
  and `node_modules` was already in sync (no `tap-spec`, no unscoped `tap-out`, no `trim` present;
  `npm ls trim` / `npm ls tap-out` both resolved to `(empty)`). This is the same recurring "stalled
  prior session already drafted (and this time partially executed) the fix, but never
  verified/logged/committed it" pattern documented in Codebase Patterns for US-005 through US-008,
  US-011, US-017, US-019, US-026, US-027, and US-028 -- now confirmed for a dependency-only story
  too, including the actual `npm uninstall`-equivalent side effect on `node_modules`, not just a
  source diff.
- Files changed:
  - `package.json`: removed `"tap-spec": "^5.0.0"` from `devDependencies` (only diff; already
    present at session start).
  - `specs/prd.json`: marked US-030 `passes: true` with notes.
- **Learnings for future iterations:**
  - No failing-test-first step applies here -- this is a pure dependency-hygiene chore, exactly the
    "pure scaffolding/config/docs tasks where a test adds no value" carve-out in the execution
    rules. There is no application behavior to assert against; the acceptance criteria's own
    verification surface (`npm audit`'s report, "test suite still runs," "typecheck passes") is
    checked directly rather than via a new unit test.
  - Verified the pre-existing removal thoroughly rather than trusting it on sight: grepped the
    whole repo (excluding `node_modules`/`.git`) for `tap-spec` and unscoped `tap-out` and found
    only two hits, both prose describing the finding itself (`SECURITY-AUDIT.md`,
    `specs/prd.json`) -- confirming the package was never actually wired into any script or source
    file. Ran `npm ls trim` and `npm ls tap-out` (both empty) and `npm install --dry-run` (only
    proposes adding the macOS-only optional `fsevents`, unrelated to this story) to confirm
    `node_modules` genuinely matches the trimmed `package.json` rather than merely looking clean by
    coincidence.
  - See the two new Codebase Patterns bullets added this session: this repo has no
    `package-lock.json` at all (nothing to diff/commit for a dependency change), and
    `SECURITY-AUDIT.md`'s checkboxes are a frozen snapshot that this project never updates when a
    finding is closed (don't check them off).
  - Full suite (`npm test`, 46645 assertions -- exactly the US-029 baseline, no new assertions
    since this story has no test-worthy behavior change), `npm run lint`, and `npx tsc --noEmit -p .`
    (only the pre-existing, documented `test/test-vectors/key-schedule.ts` `TS2769` error, confirmed
    by grepping `error TS` in the full tsc output and finding exactly one match) all pass.
